liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Deputy Prime Minister Richard Marles has revealed "about 45 Australians" are now believed to be in Gaza. It was previously believed around 19 Australians were in the enclave. Mr Marles says the 45 includes families, but couldn’t give a precise breakdown of the age of the people. Speaking on ABC News Breakfast, he said: "We are looking at ways in which, and working very hard to find ways in which, we can get those people to safety."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The UN says that vital humanitarian aid has arrived at the Egyptian side of the Rafah Crossing where thousands of Gazans have gathered, hoping to get out. Speaking to ABC News Breakfast from southern Israel, correspondent Nick Dole said while the US had given the impression talks were underway to get the flow of aid moving, there has been no progress on that front and even reports of explosions near the crossing point. As a million people are told to move into southern Gaza, placing more strain on the besieged territory, the EU has announced what it is calling humanitarian air bridges. "That's basically going to fly in a number of cargo planes into Egypt full of aid and hoping to get it to the people of Gaza, but it still needs to Rafah crossing to open," he said. US Secretary of State, Antony Blinken, has returned to Israel for the second time in days, talking with the Israeli government and trying to secure aid access. "He himself while he was here experienced of experienced one of Hamas' attacks," Dole said, "We're told by the state department he and officials had to seek shelter in one of the government offices as several barrages of rockets came over from Gaza, including some to Tel Aviv and others to Jerusalem. "There are rumours the next person to visit is Joe Biden … whether we see him or not we don't know. Certainly, if the US president were to come here to Israel, that could have real consequences for the timing of whatever Israel does in Gaza next. "It's very unlikely that with a US president present here in Israel they would launch the next stage of this campaign, one that's likely to be very long, drawn out, and bloody."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: No progress on Rafah border crossing opening, says correspondent Nick Dole from southern Israel

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: US stocks ended sharply higher on Monday as investors were optimistic about the start of earnings season, with transportation shares advancing. Investors were monitoring the Israel-Gaza war, but appeared to be taking more of a risk-on stance, with safe-haven gold prices down. Results from large banks Goldman Sachs, Bank of America, Morgan Stanley, pharmaceutical giant Johnson & Johnson, electric vehicle maker Tesla and video-streaming pioneer Netflix are due this week. Third-quarter earnings for S & P 500 companies are estimated to have increased 2.2 per cent year-over-year, according to LSEG data Friday. "At least for today (Monday), this is a market that sees a stronger earnings season, a stronger week in terms of earnings," said Quincy Krosby, chief global strategist, LPL Financial in Charlotte, North Carolina. At the same time, global leaders were trying to make sure that the Middle East conflict "remains contained," she said. The Dow Jones index rose 0.9 per cent, the S & P 500 gained 1.1 per cent and the Nasdaq Composite up 1.2 per cent.
